The Blind Leading the Blind

The Blind Leading the Blind, a series of sightless eyes and stumbling men, inspired one of the most poignant photographs of the Great War: a progression of British soldiers, blinded by poison gas, bandaged and shuffling toward the refuge of a field hospital.
Charles Baudelaire writes, “Their eyes, from which the divine spark has departed, as though they were staring into the distance, remain lifted towards the sky.”
The painter also inspired William Carlos Williams’ book of poems, Pictures from Brueghel.
The Blind Leading the Blind
The Blind Leading the Blind, also Blind or The Parable of the Blind, is a 1568 painting by Flemish renaissance artist Pieter Bruegel the Elder.
Executed in tempera on linen canvas it is the earliest painting to depict the Biblical parable of the blind leading the blind from the Gospel of Matthew 15:14.
The work is kept in the Museo di Capodimonte in Naples, Italy.
Breughel achieved such a level of Renaissance realism in The Blind Leading the Blind that the individual inflictions of each of the blind men can be determined, such as black cataracts and corneal leukemia.
The diagonal composition of The Blind Leading the Blind reinforces the off-kilter motion of the six figures falling in progression, a focus on motion that has been seen as prefiguring motion pictures.
