The Blind Leading the Blind, also Blind or The Parable of the Blind (Dutch: De parabel der blinden), is a 1568 painting by Flemish renaissance artist Pieter Bruegel the Elder.
Executed in tempera on linen canvas, it is the earliest surviving painting to depict the Biblical parable of the blind leading the blind from the Gospel of Matthew 15:14.
The work is in the collection of the Museo di Capodimonte in Naples, Italy.
The diagonal composition of The Blind Leading the Blind reinforces the off-kilter motion of the six figures falling in progression, a concern with motion that has been seen as prefiguring the advent of the motion picture medium.
The Blind Leading the Blind is considered one of the masterworks of painting for its fine, accurate detail and dynamic composition.
Copies include a larger version by Bruegel's son Pieter Brueghel the Younger, and the work has inspired literature such as poetry by Charles Baudelaire and William Carlos Williams.
—Matthew 15:14
The 86 cm × 154 cm (34 in × 61 in)[1] work is a tüchlein—a light, fragile type of painting usually meant for hanging in the home.
Tüchlein paintings often do not preserve well, but The Blind Leading the Blind has suffered no more than some abrasions.
Bruegel based the work on the Biblical parable of the blind leading the blind from the Gospel of Matthew 15:14, Christ referring to the Pharisees.
[12] Bruegel's settings tended to be fictional, but that of The Blind Leading the Blind has been identified[12] as the village Sint-Anna-Pede,[13] and the church visible as Sint-Anna Church.
The Blind Leading the Blind is one of three surviving Bruegel paintings in distemper.
Pieter Bruegel the Elder (d. 1569) achieved fame for the detailed accuracy of his realistic portrayals of common peasants.
A bitter, sorrowful tone appears in the Bruegel's last works, such as The Blind Leading the Blind and The Magpie on the Gallows.
The Blind Leading the Blind is considered one of the great masterpieces of painting.
Bruegel's depictions of beggars in paintings such as The Blind Leading the Blind left a strong influence on those who followed him, such as David Vinckboons.
Hieronymus Wierix incorporated a copy of The Blind Leading the Blind into the series Twelve Flemish Proverbs.
[30] Bruegel's son Pieter Brueghel the Younger painted a larger copy with extra details, including a flock of sheep, that now hangs in the Louvre.
French poet Charles Baudelaire's "The Blind" was inspired by Bruegel's painting.
[32] The painting was the subject of several other poems, including those by Germans Josef Weinheber and Walter Bauer,[33] and American William Carlos Williams who wrote a series of poems on Bruegel's paintings including "Parable of the Blind" which focuses on the meaning of the composition—a word that appears three times in the poems eight tercets.
